# Testing Principles

Universal testing principles, framework-agnostic. Per-framework conventions live in `../lang/typescript-testing.mdc` (Vitest), etc.

## 1. Test Pyramid

```
        E2E (5%)         ← real user journeys
      Integration (15%)  ← cross-module / DB / real I/O
     Unit (80%)          ← single functions / pure logic / fast
```

**Default to writing at the lowest layer that proves the property.** Use unit when you can — E2E is slow and fragile, reserved for critical user paths.

## 2. AAA Structure

```
// Arrange  → set up data / mocks
// Act      → trigger the behavior under test
// Assert   → verify the result
```

One AAA segment per test. **Forbidden**: one test function asserting five things; more than two assertion blocks → split.

## 3. Naming: Describe Behavior, Not Implementation

```ts
// BAD — names describe internal mechanics
it('calls db.query with correct args', () => {});
it('returns from internal cache', () => {});

// GOOD — names describe externally observable behavior
it('returns 404 when task does not exist', () => {});
it('rejects creation when title exceeds 200 chars', () => {});
it('persists the task even when notification fails', () => {});
```

Format: `it('<expected behavior> when <condition>')` or `it('<expected behavior>')`.

## 4. How Much to Write: Trigger Conditions

| Scenario | Tests required? |
|---|---|
| New logic module | **Required**: at least 1 happy path + 1 error path |
| Bug fix | **Required**: a **failing** regression test first, then the fix (red → green) |
| Refactor | Lean on existing tests as a safety net; if coverage is thin, add tests **before** refactoring |
| Public API | **Required**: contract test (the input/output schema cannot drift silently) |
| Pure UI tweaks | Visual / screenshot tests preferred; unit tests not mandatory |
| Config / deploy scripts | Usually no unit tests; rely on E2E / smoke |

### 4.1 Bug-Fix Red-Green Flow

```
1. Reproduce → write a test that **fails**
2. Run the test → red
3. Change the code → run the test → green
4. Commit (fix + regression test together)
```

**Write the test first**. If the test passes immediately, you didn't reproduce the bug or the test misses the target → rewrite the test.

## 5. Mock Boundaries

Only mock things **outside** the system:

| Mock | Don't mock |
|---|---|
| HTTP / third-party APIs | Your own services |
| DB (use in-memory / sqlite) | Business functions / pure helpers |
| Filesystem / clock | Your own models / DTOs |
| Auth providers | Your own middleware |

**The deeper you mock, the more fragile and less valuable the test.** Mocking out everything you wrote means the "test" only verifies the mock.

## 6. Coverage Philosophy

### 6.1 Stage Targets

| Module type | Target |
|---|---|
| Core business logic / algorithms | 60–80% |
| Service layer / API handlers | 50–70% |
| UI components | 30–50% (quality over quantity) |
| TUI / CLI interactions | 20–40% (manual e2e fills the gap) |
| Generated / config code | usually excluded |

### 6.2 Coverage Is Not the Goal

- 100% coverage ≠ 0 bugs; it can mean "tests don't hit the critical paths".
- 50% high-quality tests > 90% all-happy-path tests.
- **Prioritize covering**: boundary values / null / empty / error paths / concurrency.

### 6.3 Reasonable Coverage Exclusions

```
- Auto-generated code (`*.generated.*`)
- Constant / type-definition files
- Configuration / build scripts
- Test files themselves (test/ directory)
```

## 7. Test Isolation

### 7.1 No Execution-Order Dependence

```
BAD: test1 mutates global state, test2 depends on it
GOOD: each test sets up and tears down independently
```

Concurrent runs (`--test-threads=N`) and serial runs must produce identical results.

### 7.2 No External-State Dependence

```
BAD: test depends on ~/.foo/bar.json existing on your machine
GOOD: test uses a fixture / temp dir / mock fs
```

CI / teammates' machines must run successfully.

### 7.3 Time-Sensitive Tests

```
BAD: setTimeout(() => assert(...), 1000)  // timing-dependent
GOOD: inject a fake clock (vi.useFakeTimers / freezegun / mockito)
```

## 8. Anti-Patterns (Reject on Sight)

| Anti-pattern | Example | Fix |
|---|---|---|
| Tests internals | `expect(internalCache).toEqual(...)` | Test observable behavior |
| Snapshot overuse | Lots of `toMatchSnapshot()` no one reads | Explicit assertions on key fields |
| Multi-purpose test | One test triggers 5 ops + 5 assertions | Split into 5 |
| Real I/O in tests | `fetch(productionUrl)` | Mock |
| Commented-out tests | `// it.skip(...)` for a year | Delete |
| Tests with no asserts | Just runs without checking | Delete or add assertions |
| Shared mutable state | Module-level `let counter = 0` | Reset per test |

## 9. Verification Checklist

- [ ] Each test has one clear AAA segment; name describes behavior
- [ ] New logic has happy + error paths
- [ ] Bug fixes carry a red-then-green regression test
- [ ] Mocks are limited to system-external boundaries
- [ ] Tests are concurrency-safe and order-independent
- [ ] No snapshot overuse / no commented-out tests / no empty assertions

